# Anemoi inference sandbox

This sandbox was automatically generated by [evalml](https://github.com/MeteoSwiss/evalml). It contains the information to run this model:
{% if strict -%}
- checkpoint: `{{ checkpoint_path }}`
{%- else %}
- checkpoint path: `{{ checkpoint_path }}`
{%- endif %}
- python environment definition (`requirements.txt`)
{% if image -%}
- inference environment squashfs image: `{{ image }}`
{%- endif %}

It is not intended to be used for production, but only as a development and testing environment.

## Usage
{% if image %}
To set up your python environment, you have two options: using the squashfs image (on Alps) or creating your own virtual environment.
To use the squashfs image, have a look at the [CSCS documentation](https://docs.cscs.ch/guides/storage/#step-3-use-the-squashfs).
{% endif %}
To install the environment, create a virtual environment and install the dependencies:

```shell
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

You can now run a model with `anemoi-inference run config/config.yaml` (don't forget to do it on a GPU compute node).

> **Note:** `config/config.yaml` is a minimal smoke-test config — it uses `output: printer` (prints to stdout) and `input.test.use_original_paths: true` (reads from the original data paths). It is only meant to verify that the model loads and runs correctly. For real inference, use the full config{% if inference_config %} at `{{ inference_config }}`{% else %} from the evalml repository under `resources/inference/configs/`{% endif %}.

## Developing anemoi packages
The dependencies in `requirements.txt` have pinned versions based on the provenance information in the checkpoint metadata. For conveniency, we already included some anemoi packages under `libs` (the main branch on the GitHub repository at the moment of the creation of this sandbox). You can install them in editable mode with e.g.

```shell
pip install -e libs/anemoi-inference
```

Note that you might have to relax some of the pinned dependencies in order to install the latest versions. In general, we recommend NOT to touch `anemoi-models` or `anemoi-graph`, as it is very likely that it will break your model. It should generally be safe to upgrade the other anemoi packages, but there's no real guarantee (if something breaks, you have something to work on).
